Section 2 - Introduction to Statement of Operating Conditions Montana-Dakota Utilities Co. (Montana-Dakota) is a Delaware corporation duly authorized to do business in the State of Montana as a foreign corporation, and doing business in the State of Montana as a public utility. Montana-Dakota provides retail natural gas and/or electric service to areas of Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Wyoming. Montana-Dakota serves approximately 86,400 natural gas customers in 37 communities in Montana. Montana-Dakota's retail natural gas distribution operations in Montana are subject to the jurisdiction of the Montana Public Service Commission and exempt from the provisions of the Natural Gas Act (NGA) and from regulations by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) pursuant to NGA Section 1 (b) and (c).
Montana-Dakota (i.e. Transporter or the Company) has received a limited jurisdiction certificate of public convenience and necessity from FERC, pursuant to 18 C.F.R 284.224, authorizing Montana-Dakota to transport natural gas through its own facilities to interconnections with interstate pipelines for further transportation and consumption of such gas outside the State of Montana. Transporter is utilizing, for transportation service provided hereunder, the Transportation Service Rate 82 approved by the Public Service of Montana for comparable in-state transportation service.
It is the policy of Montana-Dakota to provide interruptible transportation service for any eligible Shipper (i.e. Customer) only under a written Shipper Transportation Agreement containing the terms and conditions acceptable to Montana-Dakota and in accordance with the additional terms and conditions set forth herein, executed after consideration of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, points of receipt and delivery, and other factors deemed material by Montana-Dakota and applied on a not unduly discriminatory basis.
This Statement of Operating Conditions is filed to comply with 18 C.F.R 284.123(e) and may be modified, subject to applicable approvals, as Transporter may deem appropriate and necessary.
Section 3 - Characterization of Service The service to be provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be interruptible. Transporter reserves the right to refuse the commencement of service, or to discontinue service, where, in Transporter's sole discretion, (1) the service would impair its primary public service obligation pursuant to regulation by the Montana Public Service Commission, or (2) the service would require or result in a change to Montana-Dakota's jurisdictional or regulatory status. Transporter has no standing obligations to provide service hereunder other than interruptible service which is at all times subordinate to any and all firm services provided by Montana-Dakota as part of its natural gas distribution operations.
All interruptible service is conditioned upon the availability of capacity and/or supplies sufficient to provide such service without detriment or disadvantage to customers who are dependent upon Montana-Dakota's general system supply and capacity.
Montana-Dakota shall not provide firm transportation under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
Section 4 - Authorizations Transporter's transactions entered into hereunder are based on the good faith understanding that all acts, obligations, and services performed or to be performed by Montana-Dakota hereunder, and the charges therefore, are exempt from regulation by FERC or any successor federal government authority as provided by Section 284.224 of FERC's regulations. Transporter reserves the right to terminate immediately any service hereunder, if in Transporter's sole discretion, any governmental act occurs which would require Transporter to offer or furnish service hereunder other than those contemplated in Transporter's executed Shipper Transportation Agreement or which would cause any impairment in Montana-Dakota's ability to render any service, require Montana-Dakota to offer additional service, or require a change in Montana-Dakota's jurisdictional or regulatory status.
Montana-Dakota shall file to update this Statement of Operating Conditions to reflect any new rate or surcharges that FERC, the Public Service Commission of Montana, or any other applicable regulatory agency or governmental body requires Montana-Dakota to either to bear or to collect from Customer.
Section 5 - Availability of Service This service is applicable for the transportation of natural gas, produced at a regional landfill located in Billings, Montana, to an interconnection with WBI Energy Transmission, Inc., an interstate pipeline company, using the Company's distribution facilities.
Transportation service shall be available to any qualified applicant upon the execution of a Shipper Transportation Agreement between Montana-Dakota (i.e. Transporter or the Company) and Shipper (i.e. Customer). Transporter is not required to provide any requested transportation service for which capacity is not available.
Section 6 - Statement of Rates The rates for interruptible transportation service included in this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be agreed upon between Montana-Dakota and Shipper and shall be between the maximum and minimum rates as set forth on the statement of rates submitted herewith.
Section 7 - Transportation General Terms and Conditions: A. Criteria for Service - in order to receive service, Customer must qualify for service as outlined in Section 5, Availability of Service, of this Statement of Operating Conditions and comply with the transportation general terms and conditions of the service provided herein.
B. Receipt and Delivery Obligations - Customer is responsible for making all arrangements for the delivery of said gas up to the Company's distribution system and for the transportation of said gas from the WBI interconnect to Customer's premise.
Delivery of natural gas under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be at or near points whose locations are identified within the Shipper Transportation Agreement between Transporter and Customer.
Transporter has no obligation on any day to deliver quantities of gas greater than receipts to Customer, nor to accept quantities of gas for Customer greater than deliveries accepted by the Customer.
Shipper will adhere to gas dispatching policies and procedures established by Transporter to facilitate service under the Shipper Transportation Agreement. Transporter will inform Shipper of any changes in dispatching policies that may affect the Shipper Transportation Agreement as they occur.
C. Priority of Service - The Company shall have the right to curtail or interrupt deliveries without being required to give previous notice of intention to curtail or interrupt, whenever, in its judgment, it may be necessary to do so to protect the interest of its customers whose capacity requirements are otherwise and hereby given preference. The priority of service and allocation of capacity shall be:
Priority 1 - Firm sales service. Priority 2 - Small Interruptible sales and small interruptible gas transportation service at the maximum rate on a pro rata basis. Priority 3 - Large Interruptible sales and large interruptible gas transportation service at the maximum rate on a pro rata basis. Priority 4 - Small Interruptible sales and transportation service at less than the maximum rate from the highest rate to the lowest rate and on a pro rata basis where equal rates are applicable among customers. Priority 5 - Large Interruptible sales and transportation service at less than the maximum rate from the highest rate to the lowest rate and on a pro rata basis where equal rates are applicable among customers. Priority 6 - Gas scheduled to clear imbalances.
Montana-Dakota shall have the right, in its sole discretion, to deviate from the above schedule when necessary for system operational reasons and if following the above schedule would cause an interruption in service to a customer who is not contributing to an operational problem on Montana-Dakota's system.
Montana-Dakota reserves the right to provide service to customers with a lower priority while service to higher priority customers is being curtailed due to restrictions at a given delivery or receipt point. When such restrictions are eliminated, Montana-Dakota will reinstate sales and/or transportation of gas according to each customer's original priority.
D. Penalty for Failure to Curtail or Interrupt - If Shipper fails to curtail or interrupt their use of gas hereunder when requested to do so by the Company, any gas taken above that received on Shipper's behalf, shall be billed at the charges applicable under the Company's Montana Firm General Gas Service Rate 70 (excluding the Basic Service Charge). The Cost of Gas is subject to change on a monthly basis. Please refer to the Company's website (www.montana-dakota.com <http://www.montana-dakota.com>) for the current rates applicable under this provision. In addition, the Shipper must pay an amount equal to any penalty payments or overrun charges the Company is required to make to its interconnecting pipeline(s) under the terms of its contract(s) as a result of such failure to curtail or interrupt, or $50.00 per Dk of gas used in excess of the volume of gas to which Shipper was requested to curtail or interrupt, whichever amount is greater. The Company, in its discretion, may shut off Shipper's supply of gas in the event of Shipper's failure to curtail or interrupt use of gas when requested to do so by the Company.
E. Customer's Use of Non-Delivered Volumes - In the event Shipper's gas is not being delivered to the receipt point for any reason and Shipper continues to take gas, Shipper shall be subject to any applicable penalties or charges set forth in Section 7, Paragraph D. Gas volumes supplied by Company will be charged shall be billed at the charges applicable under the Company's Montana Firm General Gas Service Rate 70 (excluding the Basic Service Charge). The Cost of Gas is subject to change on a monthly basis. Please refer to the Company's website (www.montana-dakota.com <http://www.montana-dakota.com>) for the current rates applicable under this provision. The Company is under no obligation to notify Shipper of non-delivered volumes.
F. Election of Service - Prior to the initiation of service hereunder, Shipper shall make an election of its requirements under each applicable rate schedule for the entire term of service. If mutually agreed to by the Company and customer, the term of service may be amended.
G. Reconnection Fee - Transportation customers, who cease service and then resume service within the succeeding 12 months, shall be subject to a reconnection charge of $160.00, if electronic metering must be reinstalled.
H. Balancing - 1) To the extent practicable, Shipper and the Company agree to the daily balancing of volumes of gas received and delivered on a thermal basis. Such balancing is subject to Shipper's request and the Company's discretion to vary scheduled receipts and deliveries within existing Company operating limitations.
2) In the event that the deviation between scheduled daily volumes and actual daily volumes of gas used by Shipper causes the Company to incur any additional costs from interconnecting pipeline(s), Shipper shall be solely responsible for all such penalties, fines, fees or costs incurred. If more than one Shipper has caused the Company to incur these additional costs, all costs will be prorated to each Shipper based on the Shipper's over- or under-take as a percentage of the total.
3) The Company may waive any penalty associated with Company adjustments to end-use Shipper nominations in those instances where the Company, due to operating limitations, is required to adjust end-use transportation Shipper nominations and such Company adjustments create a penalty situation or preclude Shipper from correcting an imbalance which results in a penalty.
I. Monthly Imbalance - The Shipper's monthly imbalance is the difference between the amount of gas received by Company on Shipper's behalf and the Shipper's actual metered use. Monthly imbalances will not be carried forward to the next calendar month.
a. Undertake Purchase Payment - If the monthly imbalance is due to more gas delivered on Shipper's behalf than the actual volumes used, the Company shall pay Shipper an Undertake Purchase Payment in accordance with the following schedule:
% Monthly Imbalance
Undertake Purchase Rate 0 - 5%
100% Cash-out Mechanism >5 - 10%
85% Cash-out Mechanism >10 - 15%
70% Cash-out Mechanism >15 - 20%
60% Cash-out Mechanism >20%
50% Cash-out Mechanism
Where the Cash-out Mechanism is equal to the lesser of the Company's WACOG or the Index Price, as defined in Paragraph 7.I.c.
b. Overtake Charge - If the monthly imbalance is due to more gas actually used by the Shipper than volumes delivered on their behalf, Shipper shall pay Company an Overtake Charge in accordance with the following schedule:
% Monthly Imbalance
Overtake Charge Rate 0 - 5%
100% Cash-in Mechanism >5 - 10%
115% Cash-in Mechanism >10 - 15%
130% Cash-in Mechanism >15 - 20%
140% Cash-in Mechanism >20%
150% Cash-in Mechanism
Where the Cash-in Mechanism is equal to the greater of the Company's WACOG or the Index Price, as defined in Paragraph 7.I.c.
c. The Index Price shall be the arithmetic average of the "Weekly Weighted Average Prices" published by Gas Daily for CIG Rockies and Northern Ventura during the given month. The Company's WACOG (Weighted Average Cost of Gas) includes the commodity cost of gas and applicable transportation charges including the fuel cost of transportation.
J. Daily Nomination Requirements - 1) Shipper and/or agent shall advise the Company's Gas Supply Department, via the Company's Electronic Bulletin Board in accordance with FERC timelines, of the dk requirements requested to be delivered at each delivery point during the following day. Shipper's daily nomination shall be its best estimate of the expected utilization for the gas day. Unless other arrangements are made, Shipper will be required to nominate for the non-business days involved prior to weekends and holidays.
2) All nominations should include shipper and/or agent defined begin and end dates. Shippers and/or agents may nominate for periods longer than 1 day, provided the nomination begin and end dates are within the term of the service agreement.
3) The Company has the sole right to refuse receipt of any volumes which exceed the maximum daily contract quantity and at no time shall the Company be required to accept quantities of gas for Shipper in excess of the quantities of gas to be delivered to Shipper.
4) At no time shall the Company have the responsibility to deliver gas in excess of Shipper's nomination.
K. Warranty - Agent or Shipper warrants that it will have title to all gas it tenders or causes to be tendered to the Company, and such gas shall be free and clear of all liens and adverse claims and agent, or Shipper shall indemnify the Company against all damages, costs, and expenses of any nature whatsoever arising from every claim against said gas.
L. Payment - Billed amounts will be considered past due if not paid by the due date shown on the bill. Past due bills are subject to a late payment charge of 1% per month or approximately 12% annually.
M. Billing Error - In the event an error is discovered in any bill that the Company renders to Shipper, such error shall be adjusted within a period not to exceed 6 months from the date the billing error is first discovered.
Section 8 - Metering and Measurement Transporter will meter the quantity of natural gas delivered to Customer at the delivery point identified in Shipper Transportation Agreement.
A. Remote data acquisition equipment (telemetering equipment) required by the Company for a single Shipper installation for daily measurement will be purchased and installed by the Company prior to the initiation of service hereunder.
B. The Shipper may be required, upon consultation with the Company, to contribute towards additional metering equipment necessary for daily measurement by the Company, depending on the location of the Shipper to the Company's network facilities. Enhancements and/or modifications to these services may be required to ensure equipment functionality. Such enhancements or modifications shall be completed at the direction of the Company with all associated costs the customer's responsibility. Any interruption in such services must be promptly remedied or service under this tariff will be suspended until satisfactory corrections have been made.
C. Consultation between the customer and the Company regarding telemetering requirements shall occur prior to executive of the required service agreement.
D. Customer's Meter - Customer may install, operate and maintain at its sole expense, equipment for the purpose of measuring the amount of natural gas delivered over any measurement period, provided the equipment shall not interfere with such delivery or with the Transporter's meter.
E. Alternate Means of Measurement - In the event the Transporter's meter is out of service, measurement shall be determined by the following step process beginning:
1) Using the registration of the Customer's meter, if installed and accurately registering with two percent (2%) either high or low; or 2) In the absence of accurate Customer metering, by making a calibration test or mathematical calculation, if the percentage of error is ascertainable; or 3) To the extend Customer's meter calibration test, or mathematical calculation described above cannot be utilized, by estimating by reference to quantities measured during periods under similar conditions when the Company's meter was registering accurately; or 4) To the extent the methods described above cannot be utilized, by estimating by reference to Customer's operating records for the period in question.
G. Transporter will test the meter in accordance with the applicable state utility rules and regulations. Transporter and Customer agree to the following testing and corrective procedures:
1) Testing - The accuracy of the Transporter's electronic measurement device and the integrity of the meter shall be tested and calibrated in the presence of the Shipper at a minimum of once each year. In addition, flow testing and calibration of the meter shall be performed in compliance with Transporter's testing of large gas meters. Transporter shall forward a copy of calibration documentation to Shipper. In the event that either party notifies the other that it desires a test of the accuracy of its own or of the other party's meter, the parties shall cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment.
2) Costs of Testing - Transporter shall bear the cost of the testing and any required adjustment of the Transporter's meter. In the event that Shipper requests a testing of Transporter's meter at other than the specified intervals, Shipper shall bear the cost of the testing unless such equipment is found to be inaccurate by greater than two percent (2%), higher or lower.
3) Corrections of Measuring Equipment - If, upon testing, the Transporter's meter is found to be accurate within two percent (2%), either high or low, at a flow rate corresponding to the average hourly flow rate for natural gas supplied by Transporter to Shipper for the period since the last preceding test, previous recordings of such equipment shall be considered accurate in computing deliveries of natural gas hereunder, but Transporter's meter shall be promptly adjusted to record correctly to the extent possible. If, upon testing, Transporter's meter shall be found to be inaccurate by greater than two percent (2%), either high or low, at a flow rate corresponding to the average hourly flow rate for natural gas as supplied by Transporter to Shipper for the period since the last preceding test, then such Transporter meter shall be promptly adjusted to record properly, to the extent possible, and any previous recordings by such Transporter meter shall be corrected to zero error, to the extent possible, and Transporter shall promptly send to Shipper a report based on such corrected recordings and a revised invoice based on corrected readings within thirty days. If no reliable information exists as to when the Company meter became inaccurate, it shall be assumed for correction purposes hereunder that such inaccuracy began at a point in time midway between the testing date and the last previous date on which the Transporter meter was tested and found to be accurate or adjusted to be accurate.
4) Maintenance - Each party shall have the right to be present whenever the other party reads, cleans, changes, repairs, inspects, tests, calibrates, or adjusts its meter. Each party shall give timely notice to the other party in advance of taking any such actions.
5) Charges, Penalties, Costs or Expenses - To the extent that any penalties are incurred by Shipper as a result of the inaccuracy of Transporter's meter greater than two percent (2%), either high or low, Transporter shall be responsible for such penalties.
6) Record Examination - Shipper shall have the right at all reasonable times to examine the books, records, and charts of Transporter, for a two year period subsequent to the issuance in writing of a dispute, invoice, to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, charge, or computation made under or pursuant to any provisions of this agreement.
Section 9 - Definitions Customer - used interchangeable with Shipper in this Statement of Operating Conditions and Shipper Transportation Agreement.
Delivery Point - the point at which Shipper assumes custody of the gas being transported. This point will normally be at the outlet of Transporter's meter(s).
Gas Day - a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours, beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time.
Interruption - a cessation of transportation or retail natural gas service deemed necessary by the Transporter.
Nomination - the daily volume, in Dk, of natural gas requested by Customer for transportation and delivery to Customer at the delivery point over a 24 hour period commencing at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time each day.
Receipt Point - the intertie between the Transporter and the interconnecting pipeline(s).
Transporter - used interchangeably with Montana-Dakota or the Company in this Statement of Operating Conditions and Shipper Transportation Agreement.
Section 10 - Assignment Customer agrees that it will not assign the Shipper Transportation Agreement except upon written consent of Transporter.
Section 11 - Indemnification Customer agrees to indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from any and all injury, loss or damage resulting from Customer's negligent or wrongful acts under and during the term of the Shipper Transportation Agreement between Transporter and Customer. Transporter agrees to indemnify and hold Customer harmless from any and all injury, loss or damage resulting from Transporter's negligent or wrongful acts under and during the term of the Shipper Agreement between Transporter and Customer.
Section 12 - Ingress and Egress Transporter is hereby granted rights of ingress and egress, at reasonable times, for operating, inspecting and maintaining any of Transporter's facilities on Customer's premise.
Section 13 - Force Majeure In the event of either party being rendered wholly or in part by force majeure unable to carry out its obligations, then the obligations of the parties hereto, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused. Such causes or contingencies affecting the performance by either party, however, shall not relieve it of liability in the event of its concurring negligence or in the event of its failure to use due diligence to remedy the situation and remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch, nor shall such causes or contingencies affecting the performance relieve either party from its obligations to make payments of amounts then due hereunder, nor shall such causes or contingencies relieve either party of liability unless such party shall give notice and full particulars of the same in writing or by telephone to the other party as soon as possible after the occurrence relied on. If volumes of customer's gas are destroyed while in the Transporter's possession by an event of force majeure, the obligations of the parties shall terminate with respect to the volumes lost.
The term "force majeure" as employed herein shall include, but shall not be limited to, acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, failure to perform by any third party, which performance is necessary to the performance by either customer or the Company, acts of the public enemy or terrorists, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrest and restraint of rulers and peoples, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe, line freeze ups, sudden partial or sudden entire failure of gas supply, failure to obtain materials and supplies due to governmental regulations, and causes of like or similar kind, whether herein enumerated or not, and not within the control of the party claiming suspension, and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to overcome; provided that the exercise of due diligence shall not require settlement of labor disputes against the better judgment of the party having the dispute.
The term "force majeure" as employed herein shall also include, but shall not be limited to, inability to obtain or acquire, at reasonable cost, grants, servitudes, rights-of-way, permits, licenses or any other authorizations from third parties or agencies (private or governmental) or inability to obtain or acquire at reasonable cost necessary materials or supplies to construct, maintain and operate any facilities required for the performance of any obligations under this agreement, when any such inability directly or indirectly contributes to or results in either party's inability to perform its obligations.
Section 14 - Regulatory Authority This Statement of Operating Conditions and execution of Shipper Transportation Agreement is subject to all valid laws, orders, rules and regulations of any and all duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction over the subject matter herein and is subject to the receipt of any necessary authorization for the transportation service contemplated herein
Section 15 - Reporting Requirements Shipper shall furnish all information as may be required or appropriate to comply with reporting requirements of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction over the matters herein.
